SIMPLE: moralize
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Moralize
<hw>Mor"al*ize</hw> <pr>(m⟦ocr⟧r"⟦ait⟧l*⟦imac⟧z)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Moralized</conjf>
<pr>(m⟦ocr⟧r"⟦ait⟧l*⟦imac⟧zd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Moralizing</conjf>
<pr>(m⟦ocr⟧r"⟦ait⟧l*⟦imac⟧*z⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>moraliser</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To apply to a moral
purpose; to explain in a moral sense; to draw a moral from.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This fable is <qex>moralized</qex> in a common proverb.</q>
<rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Did he not <qex>moralize</qex> this spectacle?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To furnish with moral lessons, teachings, or
examples; to lend a moral to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While chastening thoughts of sweetest use, bestowed⟦br⟧
By Wisdom, <qex>moralize</qex> his pensive road.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To render moral; to correct the morals of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It had a large share in <qex>moralizing</qex> the poor white
people of the country.</q> <rj><qau>D. Ramsay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To give a moral quality to; to affect the moral
quality of, either for better or worse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Good and bad stars <qex>moralize</qex> not our actions.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moralize</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Moralize
<hw>Mor"al*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
make moral reflections; to regard acts and events as involving a
moral.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>to lecture to a person in a manner asserting moral
principles.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> sermonize, preachify, moralise.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moralizer</ent>⟦br⟧
